{"cursor":"19147","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"{{Infobox person |name = Jacob Schiff |image = JacobSchiff.jpg |caption =\n|birth_name=Jakob Heinrich Schiff |birth_date = |birth_place = Frankfurt,\nGermany |death_date = |death_place = New York City, New York, U.S. |other_names\n= |known_for = |occupation = Banker and businessman |nationality =\nGerman American |spouse=Therese Loeb (2 children) }} 'Jacob Henry Schiff'\n(born 'Jakob Heinrich Schiff'; January 10, 1847 â September 25, 1920) was an\nAmerican banker, businessman, and philanthropist. He helped finance, among many\nother things, the Japanese military efforts against Tsarist Russia in the Russo-\nJapanese War.\n\nBorn in Frankfurt, Germany, Schiff migrated to the United States after the Civil\nwar, and joined the firm Kuhn, Loeb & Co. http://www.jewishencyclopedia.com/articles/13266-\nschiff From his base on Wall Street, he was the foremost Jewish leader\nfrom 1880 to 1920 in what later became known as the \"Schiff era\", grappling with\nall major Jewish issues and problems of the day, including the plight of Russian\nJews under the Tsar, American and international anti-semitism, care of needy\nJewish immigrants, and the rise of Zionism. Naomi Wiener Cohen, [http://boo-\nks.google.com.ph/books?id=fpIOia8QxyYC&pg=PP4&lpg=PP4&dq=%22Schiff+era%22+%22Wa-\nll+Street%22&source=bl&ots=wvHPLpds0v&sig=8WVcImjf-a-\nLxiypga0uxLqLUbk&hl=en&ei=3AVmTKqWApSrcZTf0cAP&sa=X&oi=book_result&ct=result&re-\nsnum=10&ved=0CD4Q6AEwCQ#v=onepage&q=%22Schiff%20era%22%20%22Wall%20Street%22&f=-\nfalse Jacob H. Schiff: a study in American Jewish leadership] Glazer,\nN (1957) American Judaism, UCP. He also became the director of many\nimportant corporations, including the National City Bank of New York, Equitable\nLife Assurance Society, Wells Fargo & Company, and the Union Pacific Railroad.\nIn many of his interests he was associated with E.H. Harriman.\n","linknr":343,"url":"Jacob_Schiff","recorded":1363425200,"lin